external_knowledge:
- High turnover rate refers to enzymes with a kcat_value > 100, indicating they can process a large number of substrate molecules per unit time;
- Top-performing enzymes are those with the highest vmax_value (maximum reaction rate) for each enzyme type;
- Michaelis constant (Km) is a measure of the affinity of an enzyme for its substrate, with lower values indicating higher affinity.

sql:
SELECT subsystem_name
FROM subsystem
WHERE subsystem_type = 'Signaling';

external_knowledge:
- Km value is a measure of the binding affinity of an enzyme for its substrate, with lower values indicating higher affinity. A Km value less than 0.1 indicates high affinity and is likely an example condition; 
- Pathway complexity score is a measure of the complexity of a biochemical pathway, with higher scores indicating more complex pathways. A pathway complexity score greater than 3 is an example condition to filter more complex pathways; 
- Signaling subsystems are a type of biochemical subsystem involved in signal transduction, which is the process by which a cell converts one kind of signal or stimulus into another; 
- Enzymes are biological molecules, typically proteins, that significantly speed up the rate of virtually all of the chemical reactions that take place within cells.

sql:
SELECT abbreviation, description
FROM enzymes
WHERE molecular_weight > (SELECT AVG(molecular_weight) FROM enzymes);

SELECT organism, COUNT(enzyme_id) AS enzyme_count, AVG(molecular_weight) AS avg_molecular_weight
FROM enzymes
GROUP BY organism;

SELECT AVG(km_value) AS average_km_value
FROM enzyme_kinetics
WHERE km_value IS NOT NULL;

SELECT enzyme_id, AVG(activity_temperature) AS avg_activity_temperature
FROM enzymes
GROUP BY enzyme_id;

SELECT ek.enzyme_id
FROM enzyme_kinetics AS ek
WHERE ek.km_value = 0.15;
